23:47.920 --> 23:54.280
Yesterday we discussed Farmer's pension for writing under pseudonyms, as it turns out this practice has a very desirable side effect.

23:55.460 --> 24:04.100
One of the funny things about this is that I found out that I could use the fictional author device to break a writing block.

24:04.380 --> 24:10.480
I had a writing block once, that terrible thing that sometimes happens to writers.

24:11.780 --> 24:14.480
They don't know what caused this for some reason.

24:15.220 --> 24:19.820
They might have many ideas, be eager to go, but when they sit down in front of a typewriter nothing happens.

24:21.620 --> 24:23.540
Well, that happened to me once.

24:24.400 --> 24:27.160
I never thought it would. I thought it was immune to such a thing.

24:27.820 --> 24:28.300
But it did.

24:29.240 --> 24:33.800
And after a wrestling for two months and getting no place, I had an idea.

24:35.460 --> 24:45.280
I sat down with the typewriter and wrote a story, not by Philip Jose Farmer, but by David Copperfield, I'd say.

24:45.280 --> 24:47.760
I don't remember which particular nominative.

24:49.920 --> 24:55.980
The story poured out. Very good. I thought so anyway.

24:57.480 --> 25:00.480
When I'd completed that, the writing block was gone.

25:01.020 --> 25:06.600
See, I wasn't writing then as me, or Philip Jose Farmer, but as a Gilbert Trout.

25:07.880 --> 25:10.380
And I was in his shoes. I had no trouble.

25:10.380 --> 25:18.540
The funny thing about this is, it's a psychological trick that I'm conscious of.

25:21.060 --> 25:22.440
And yet it works.

25:24.300 --> 25:29.020
It's not like I'm trying to trick my unconscious, but I must be doing it one way or another.

25:31.940 --> 25:37.900
I don't know if anybody else has ever broken a writer's block in that manner, but I recommend trying it.

25:39.180 --> 25:43.840
Farmer has also written several books featuring Tarzan or Tarzan-like characters.

25:44.420 --> 25:46.420
Tarzan Alive is Tarzan's biography.

25:47.100 --> 25:52.260
The erotic novel A Feast Unknown and its clean sequels The Mad Goblin and Lord of the Trees

25:52.260 --> 25:55.680
feature thinly veiled versions of Tarzan and Doc Savage.

25:56.220 --> 26:02.300
Lord Tiger, the Opar books, and the Adventures of the Peerless Peer also have Tarzan-like protagonists.

26:02.760 --> 26:05.480
We asked Farmer when he developed his interest in Tarzan.

26:06.360 --> 26:14.660
I first read Tarzan when I guess I was about seven or eight years old, and I became wrapped up in that early age with the words of,

26:14.660 --> 26:17.480
like your eyes swirls.

26:19.220 --> 26:24.360
But when I started college, I kind of lost interest and didn't read him anymore.

26:29.980 --> 26:34.780
But later Farmer picked up on Tarzan again. This time he saw Tarzan in a different light.

26:35.920 --> 26:48.800
When I started reading the books about Tarzan again, and this time, although I still kept a lot of my childhood interest in him,

26:50.300 --> 26:55.240
I began seeing things in Tarzan, for instance, that had not been seen before.

26:56.760 --> 27:06.240
It was not just a child who'd been cast away and raised by great apes and then become a creature of the jungle,

27:06.240 --> 27:18.180
then returned to claim his fortune. He was sort of an archetype of many, many heroes from classical myth.

27:19.420 --> 27:24.060
And now I'm sure that when Burroughs wrote this, he didn't know what he was doing, but he did it unconsciously.

27:24.680 --> 27:27.600
I think it's the creation of Tarzan and the Stroke of Genius.

27:28.540 --> 27:34.800
Burroughs is not a great writer, but he has created a great character just like Aikon and Doyle.

27:35.340 --> 27:39.960
He created a great character, Sherlock Holmes.

27:41.060 --> 27:48.760
Philip Jose Farmer, an author with a seemingly endless supply of unique ideas who appears just now to be gaining widespread acceptance.

